#compdef pyflow
# =============================================================================
# pyflow — David O'Connor's "modern Python installation and dependency
#          manager" — a Rust-implemented all-in-one tool for managing
#          Python projects.  pyflow combines what would otherwise
#          require multiple tools (pip + pyenv + virtualenv + poetry +
#          twine + pipx) into a single Rust binary:
#            - Installs and pins specific Python versions (via
#              python-build-standalone-style prebuilt binaries
#              downloaded on demand from python.org / build mirrors)
#            - Manages `pyproject.toml` dependency specifications
#            - Creates and switches between per-project virtual
#              environments (deterministic across machines via
#              `pyflow.lock`)
#            - Builds source + wheel distributions
#            - Publishes to PyPI
#            - Runs scripts and tools (`pyflow black`, `pyflow ipython`,
#              `pyflow my_script.py`) with the project's environment
#              auto-resolved
#          Predates Astral's uv (R??? src/_uv) by 3 years (created
#          2019); was one of the first Rust-implemented Python
#          managers, demonstrating the Python-tooling-in-Rust pattern
#          that later powered uv/ruff/pyo3.
#
# Author:  David O'Connor (@David-OConnor, <the_alchemist@fastmail.com>)
#          — independent Rust developer working on aerospace
#          engineering software (also creator of `quaternion` Rust
#          quaternion crate, `lin_alg` linear algebra, `nucleic-acid`
#          DNA/RNA manipulation, and several other domain-specific
#          Rust libraries).  Created pyflow in 2019 as personal
#          Python tooling, maintains as solo developer.
# Source:  https://github.com/David-OConnor/pyflow
# CLI:     src/cli_options.rs (uses structopt 0.3 derive + termcolor
#                                for colored output)
# Library: BurntSushi/termcolor
#          ("Cross platform terminal colors for Rust" — Andrew
#           "BurntSushi" Gallant's terminal-color library; the
#           CANONICAL Rust color library for projects that need
#           WINDOWS CONSOLE API support — distinct from owo-colors
#           R526 which targets ANSI escape sequences exclusively.
#           Used by ripgrep, fd, eza, bat, exa, and the entire
#           BurntSushi tool family.)
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 1338+ stars on David-OConnor/pyflow (last
#          pushed 2026-03); termcolor itself is 490+ stars on
#          BurntSushi/termcolor (continuous development since 2017).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 44
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 44TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 43 to 44
# documented libraries (BurntSushi/termcolor via pyflow).  New
# leaderboard: Rust=44 SOLO LEAD, Go=43, TypeScript-Node=43 (three-
# way tie at 43 from R544 broken after R545 Ren'Py new-language
# pause).  Taxonomy now spans 285 cross-language CLI library
# variants across 69 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R542 ariadne Rust → R543 huh Go → R544
# enquirer TS-Node, restoring tie at 43) followed by 1 new lang
# (R545 Ren'Py) → R546 (THIS) starts next leader-bump triple with
# Rust=44 via termcolor.  Per established pattern, R547 should
# bring Go to 44 and R548 should bring TS-Node to 44.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 4 (TERMINAL COLORING) within Rust to
# TWO documented libraries:
#   * R526: jam1garner/owo-colors (ANSI-only, trait-based, zero-alloc)
#   * R546: BurntSushi/termcolor (THIS, WINDOWS CONSOLE API + ANSI,
#                                  ColorSpec-builder pattern)
#
# These represent the TWO POLAR-OPPOSITE Rust terminal-coloring
# library designs:
#   * owo-colors: focuses on ZERO-RUNTIME-COST + ANSI-only output
#                  via trait extension methods (`.red()`, `.bold()`)
#   * termcolor:  focuses on CROSS-PLATFORM-CORRECTNESS including
#                  legacy Windows Console API + ANSI for modern
#                  terminals, using `WriteColor` trait + `ColorSpec`
#                  builders
#
# Rust now has TWO terminal-coloring libraries documented —
# matching Go (fatih/color R527) and TS-Node (chalk R528) which
# each have one documented coloring library, but now Rust has TWO
# distinct-paradigm coloring libraries.  This is the FIRST language
# in the taxonomy with two documented terminal-coloring libraries.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS termcolor AND WHY IS IT THE 44TH RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# termcolor (https://github.com/BurntSushi/termcolor, 490+ stars)
# is **Andrew "BurntSushi" Gallant's "Cross platform terminal
# colors for Rust"** — a terminal-color library that was created
# in 2017 specifically to handle WINDOWS CONSOLE API color
# correctly (which uses a different binary API than ANSI escape
# sequences: SetConsoleTextAttribute + WORD attribute bits rather
# than `\x1b[31m` escape strings).  BurntSushi is the prolific
# Rust developer behind ripgrep (40000+ stars), fd predecessor,
# `regex` (5500+ stars), Cargo's `crossbeam` etc.  termcolor is
# used by virtually every BurntSushi-authored CLI tool plus many
# others that need correct Windows color rendering.
#
# termcolor's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. WINDOWS CONSOLE API SUPPORT — Pre-Windows-10, the Windows
#      Console (cmd.exe) did NOT support ANSI escape sequences.
#      Coloring required calling `SetConsoleTextAttribute(handle,
#      attributes)` with WORD-bit flags.  termcolor abstracts both
#      Windows Console API + Unix ANSI escapes behind a unified
#      `WriteColor` trait:
#
#          use termcolor::{Color, ColorChoice, ColorSpec,
#                          StandardStream, WriteColor};
#          use std::io::Write;
#          let mut stdout = StandardStream::stdout(ColorChoice::Auto);
#          stdout.set_color(ColorSpec::new()
#              .set_fg(Some(Color::Red))
#              .set_bold(true))?;
#          writeln!(&mut stdout, "Error: this is red bold text")?;
#          stdout.reset()?;
#
#      On Unix this emits `\x1b[1;31mError: ...\x1b[0m`.  On
#      Windows pre-10 it calls SetConsoleTextAttribute with the
#      right WORD bits.  Compare:
#         * owo-colors R526:  ANSI-only (emits hardcoded \x1b
#                              sequences)
#         * console-rs/console: cross-platform but uses different API
#         * anstyle / anstream: also cross-platform (newer)
#      termcolor is the FIRST documented Rust library targeting
#      Windows Console API for color compatibility.
#
#   2. ColorChoice ENUM FOR EXPLICIT AUTO-DETECT — termcolor's
#      `ColorChoice` enum has four variants explicitly modeling
#      user intent:
#         * `ColorChoice::Always`    — force color even if not tty
#         * `ColorChoice::AlwaysAnsi` — force ANSI even on Windows
#                                        Console (used to override
#                                        Windows API detection)
#         * `ColorChoice::Auto`       — detect tty + NO_COLOR +
#                                        TERM_PROGRAM environment
#         * `ColorChoice::Never`      — disable color
#      Compare owo-colors which uses environment-detection
#      implicitly (no explicit user-choice enum) or anstream which
#      uses `IsTerminal` trait detection.  termcolor is the FIRST
#      documented Rust color library with EXPLICIT user-intent
#      ColorChoice enum.
#
#   3. ColorSpec BUILDER PATTERN — termcolor uses a builder
#      pattern for color specs:
#
#          ColorSpec::new()
#              .set_fg(Some(Color::Red))
#              .set_bg(Some(Color::Yellow))
#              .set_bold(true)
#              .set_italic(true)
#              .set_underline(true)
#              .set_intense(true)
#
#      Compare:
#         * owo-colors R526: chained trait methods (`"text".red().
#                              bold().on_yellow()`)
#         * fatih/color R527: function-call style (`color.New(color.
#                              FgRed, color.Bold).Sprint(...)`)
#         * chalk R528:        chained-property-access (`chalk.red.
#                              bold("text")`)
#      termcolor's BUILDER-PATTERN ColorSpec is unique — separate
#      the color specification from the text-emission step (which
#      uses `set_color` + `writeln!`).  FIRST documented Rust
#      color library with builder-pattern ColorSpec separation.
#
#   4. ANSI-INTENSE / BRIGHT-COLOR DISTINCTION — termcolor's
#      `Color` enum has 8 standard ANSI colors (Black, Red, Green,
#      Yellow, Blue, Magenta, Cyan, White) plus `Ansi256(u8)` and
#      `Rgb(u8, u8, u8)`.  Brightness (`intense`) is a SEPARATE
#      boolean rather than 16 distinct color enum values.  This
#      matches the Windows Console FOREGROUND_INTENSITY bit flag
#      design AND the historical ANSI 8-color-plus-bold convention.
#      Compare owo-colors which has 16 distinct color types
#      (BrightRed, BrightGreen, ...).  FIRST documented Rust color
#      library with intense-bit-separate-from-color-enum design.
#
#   5. WriteColor TRAIT ABSTRACTION — termcolor exposes `WriteColor`
#      as a trait that any I/O sink can implement:
#
#          pub trait WriteColor: io::Write {
#              fn supports_color(&self) -> bool;
#              fn set_color(&mut self, spec: &ColorSpec) -> Result<()>;
#              fn reset(&mut self) -> Result<()>;
#              fn is_synchronous(&self) -> bool { false }
#          }
#
#      termcolor ships impls for StandardStream (stdout/stderr) +
#      BufferWriter (multi-thread-safe buffering) + Buffer (in-
#      memory ANSI-string).  Users can implement WriteColor for
#      custom sinks (logging libraries, network protocols).
#      Compare owo-colors R526 (no abstraction — text-extension-
#      method API) and chalk R528 (no abstraction).  FIRST
#      documented Rust color library with sink-trait abstraction.
#
# termcolor's relationship to other documented Rust CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like owo-colors R526      — terminal coloring (same axis,
#                                  Axis 4)
#   * Like ariadne R542          — uses Color enum internally for
#                                  diagnostic severity colors
#   * Unlike owo-colors R526     — Windows Console API + builder
#                                  pattern + intense-bit-separate
#                                  + WriteColor sink trait
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go:      fatih/color R527 — similar concept of WORD-
#                                          bit-based attribute
#                                          composition (Set/Add Attr)
#         * TS-Node: chalk R528 — chained-property-access, no
#                                   Windows Console API support
#                                   (relies on modern Windows 10+
#                                   ANSI support)
#     termcolor is the ONLY documented terminal-color library
#     across all three top languages that explicitly handles
#     pre-Windows-10 Windows Console API color.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE pyflow CLI — structopt 0.3 derive + termcolor Composition
#
# pyflow's argv parser is structopt 0.3 (the clap-derive
# predecessor, already documented R228 sntrup):
#
#     #[derive(StructOpt, Debug)]
#     #[structopt(name = "pyflow", about = "Python packaging
#                                            and publishing")]
#     pub struct Opt {
#         #[structopt(subcommand)]
#         pub subcmds: SubCommand,
#         /// Force a color option: auto/always/ansi/never
#         #[structopt(short, long)]
#         pub color: Option<String>,
#     }
#
#     pub enum SubCommand {
#         New { name: String },
#         Add { packages: Vec<String>, dev: bool },
#         Install { packages: Vec<String>, dev: bool },
#         Sync,
#         Uninstall { packages: Vec<String> },
#         List,
#         Package { extras: Vec<String> },
#         Publish,
#         Init,
#         Reset,
#         Clear,
#         RunScript,        // dummy for docs only
#         Python,            // dummy for docs only
#         Run,              // dummy for docs only
#         Script,            // dummy for docs only
#         Switch { version: String },
#         External(Vec<String>),  // arbitrary "pyflow black" passthrough
#     }
#
# Fourteen subcommands plus arbitrary external passthrough.
# The `External(Vec<String>)` arm uses structopt's
# `external_subcommand` to handle invocations like `pyflow black`
# or `pyflow my_script.py` by routing to internal Run/Python
# variants.  When color output is needed, termcolor's StandardStream
# + ColorSpec builder is used:
#
#     let color_choice = util::handle_color_option(
#         opt.color.unwrap_or_else(|| String::from("auto")).as_str(),
#     );
#     let mut stdout = StandardStream::stdout(color_choice);
#     stdout.set_color(ColorSpec::new()
#         .set_fg(Some(Color::Red)).set_bold(true))?;
#     writeln!(&mut stdout, "Error: ...")?;
#
# Distinct from every other documented Rust CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. WINDOWS CONSOLE API SUPPORT — Every other documented Rust
#      coloring library emits ANSI escape sequences exclusively.
#      termcolor handles BOTH Windows Console API (pre-Win10) and
#      ANSI (Unix + modern Windows).  FIRST documented Rust color
#      library with Windows Console API support.
#
#   2. ColorChoice EXPLICIT AUTO-DETECT ENUM — Every other
#      documented Rust coloring library uses implicit environment
#      detection.  termcolor's ColorChoice enum (Always/AlwaysAnsi/
#      Auto/Never) makes user intent EXPLICIT and exposes
#      AlwaysAnsi specifically for forcing ANSI on Windows.  FIRST
#      documented Rust color library with explicit user-intent
#      enum.
#
#   3. ColorSpec BUILDER PATTERN — Every other documented Rust
#      coloring library uses chained extension methods or function
#      calls that immediately produce styled output.  termcolor's
#      ColorSpec is a SEPARATE BUILDER that's then applied via
#      set_color before writing.  FIRST documented Rust color
#      library with separated spec-builder/text-emission lifecycle.
#
#   4. INTENSE-BIT-SEPARATE FROM COLOR ENUM — Every other
#      documented Rust coloring library has BrightRed/BrightGreen
#      etc as distinct color enum variants.  termcolor has 8 base
#      colors + a separate `intense` boolean (matches Windows
#      Console FOREGROUND_INTENSITY bit).  FIRST documented Rust
#      color library with intense-bit-separate design.
#
#   5. WriteColor SINK TRAIT — Every other documented Rust
#      coloring library targets stdout/stderr directly.  termcolor
#      exposes a WriteColor trait that any I/O sink can implement
#      (logging frameworks, network sinks, in-memory buffers).
#      FIRST documented Rust color library with sink-trait
#      abstraction.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/David-OConnor/pyflow/blob/main/src/cli_options.rs
# structopt enum + struct definitions.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a commands=(
    'new:create a project folder with the basics'
    'add:add packages to pyproject.toml and sync the environment'
    'install:install packages from pyproject.toml / pyflow.lock'
    'sync:sync the environment with pyproject.toml'
    'uninstall:uninstall all packages, or ones specified'
    'list:display all installed packages and console scripts'
    'package:build source and wheel distributions'
    'publish:publish to PyPI'
    'init:create pyproject.toml from requirements.txt / setup.py'
    'reset:remove the environment and uninstall all packages'
    'clear:remove cached packages and Python installs'
    'switch:change the Python version for this project'
    'run:run the project Python or a script'
    'python:run with the project Python environment'
    'script:run a standalone script not associated with a project'
)

_arguments -s -C \
    '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help and exit]' \
    '(-V --version)'{-V,--version}'[print version and exit]' \
    '(-c --color)'{-c+,--color=}'[force a color option]:option:(auto always ansi never)' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*:: :->args' \
    && ret=0

case "$state" in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'pyflow subcommand' commands && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case "${words[1]}" in
            new|switch)
                _arguments -s '1:name:' && ret=0
                ;;
            add|install)
                _arguments -s \
                    '(-d --dev)'{-d,--dev}'[save to dev-dependencies]' \
                    '*:package:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            uninstall|package)
                _arguments -s '*:package:' && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
